1A. OWNER'S CURRENT AND FORMER EMPLOYERS EXCEPTION
--------------------------------------------------
As an exception to Sections 2 and 3, the copyright holder (the
"Owner") grants a royalty-free, worldwide, non-exclusive,
non-transferable license to use, deploy, self-host, and internally
distribute the Software for internal business purposes -- including
ordinary commercial and operational use -- to:

  (i)  the legal entity that currently employs, retains, or contracts
       with the Owner (the "Owner's Current Employer"); and

  (ii) any legal entity that has previously employed, retained, or
       contracted with the Owner under a bona fide employment,
       independent-contractor, or consulting relationship (each, a
       "Owner's Former Employer"; collectively with the Owner's
       Current Employer, the "Permitted Employers").

This exception extends to the directors, officers, employees, and
contractors of any Permitted Employer when they are acting within the
scope of their roles for that Permitted Employer.

This exception is subject to the following clarifications and limits:

  (a) Scope of use. The exception is for the Permitted Employer's
      own internal business needs, including self-hosting on
      infrastructure that the Permitted Employer owns, leases, or
      operates for itself. It attaches independently to each
      Permitted Employer and, in the case of an Owner's Former
      Employer, survives the end of the Owner's engagement with that
      entity (so an Owner's Former Employer may continue to self-host
      and use the Software on the same internal-use terms after the
      Owner has moved on).

  (b) No resale or hosting-as-a-service. The exception is internal-use
      only. It does NOT permit any Permitted Employer to redistribute,
      resell, sublicense, host as a service to third parties, package
      into a commercial product, white-label, repackage, or otherwise
      convey the Software (in source or compiled form, modified or
      unmodified) to anyone outside that Permitted Employer.

  (c) No external Pharos-branded offering. A Permitted Employer may
      use intelligence, reports, and analysis that it generates with
      the Software for its own purposes (including incorporating such
      output into work products it delivers to its own customers in
      the ordinary course of its business), but may NOT market, brand,
      identify, or hold out any external offering as "Pharos", "powered
      by Pharos", or under any colorable variant of the Pharos name,
      lighthouse logo, or "A beam through the noise" tagline.

  (d) No branding alteration. The exception does NOT permit a
      Permitted Employer to remove, alter, or replace the Pharos
      branding, logos, copyright notices, or this license text in any
      copy of the Software it deploys.

  (e) No trademark grant. No Permitted Employer is granted any rights
      in the Pharos name, logo, or trademarks for marketing, product
      naming, or external-facing materials.

  (f) Bona fide relationship required. A "Owner's Former Employer"
      must have engaged the Owner under a bona fide employment,
      independent-contractor, or consulting agreement of more than
      de minimis duration and substance. Brief, one-time, gratuitous,
      merely prospective, or purely ceremonial engagements (including
      interviews, unpaid trial tasks, single-day events, hackathons,
      shadow days, and similar) do NOT, on their own, establish an
      Owner's Former Employer for purposes of this exception.

  (g) Affiliates not automatically included. The exception attaches
      to the specific legal entity that employed or retained the
      Owner. It does NOT automatically extend to that entity's parent
      companies, subsidiaries, affiliates, joint ventures, business
      partners, successors-in-interest, or acquirers, unless the Owner
      expressly says so in writing in the official repository. If a
      Permitted Employer is acquired by, merged into, or reorganized
      under a different legal entity, that successor entity must
      either (i) obtain the Owner's written confirmation that the
      exception transfers, or (ii) bring the Software under a
      commercial license pursuant to Section 3.

  (h) Owner's discretion. The Owner may, at the Owner's sole
      discretion and at any time, extend, narrow, suspend, or revoke
      this exception -- in whole, or with respect to any specific
      Permitted Employer -- by publishing notice in the official
      repository. Any such change takes effect on publication. A
      revocation does not retroactively invalidate prior good-faith
      use, but the affected Permitted Employer must thereafter cease
      use or obtain a commercial license under Section 3.

  (i) No relationship implied. This exception does not create any
      employment, partnership, agency, support, or maintenance
      relationship between the Owner and any Permitted Employer with
      respect to the Software, and does not obligate the Owner to
      provide any support, warranty, maintenance, or further
      development.

For the avoidance of doubt: this exception is purely a courtesy
carve-out granted by the Owner. It does NOT make the Software open
source, "freely available for enterprise use", or available to
organizations generally; it applies only to Permitted Employers as
defined above. It does NOT extend to any organization that has not
been a bona fide employer, contractor-engager, or consulting client
of the Owner, and it does NOT extend to such an entity's parents,
subsidiaries, affiliates, joint ventures, business partners,
successors, or acquirers unless the Owner expressly says so in
writing in the official repository.


